Editorials . . .
projects — but only more war
The recent peace concentrations in Des points, New York
and other parts of the country have been overshadowed by the
booking of Haiphong and the prospects for a continuing escape—
tion of the Vietnam war. Most Americans did not need the words
of an anonymous military official who said the Haiphong attack
was a “tremendously important intensification of the air war"
1(quoted from the Des joined Register, April 21), As the war grows
in seriousness and the numbers of warranties mount (this year probably more American soldiers will he killed than during the peak
of the Korean War) the possibilities for peace seem very dim,
Most Americans still go along with the war effort and Congress
in as willing as ever to provide the millions of dollars needed to
continue the conflict. Yet, as the recent concentrations indicate,
more and more Americans are willing to take some positive nation
to protest of the war. We were greatly encouraged by the number of students (and even some faculty members) who went to the
Des joined march. While it may be effectively argued that protest:
"don't do any good" it may also be argued that larger and mom
military projects might cause some federation of the Johnson
policy. And it is also probably true that active responsible protest
is the only means of effective expression left open to those opposed
to the war effort and the current direction of American foreign
policy it is easy to despite of the present situation, but a moral
commitment to peace processes giving up protest and building
to those in power.
— K. N.
The ”Riot” — only oi simpson
The excessive drinking and property destruction which occur
on “Spring Riot" night are symptoms of a Grinnell social problem
which drivers only in degree and not in kind from the usual. The
administration‘s decision to english the “Riot” may indeed be sustained by the very intensity of these symptoms, but fails to come to
trips with the problems which are not peculiar to that night and
were, in fact, less severe in this year’l "Riot" than in previous
years!
"Riot” night was only one additional indication that Grinnell
men and women do not lmow how to meet and enjoy one another
when the social communities are removed. Instead, as on this Spring
night, they drink exclusively and wonder formerly around the campus waiting for a seasonal miracle to sweet them off their feet
Grinnell is a difficult place for many people to meet members
or the opposite set. The physical separation of the computer. along
with the separate dining rooms, force them to rely on communities.
In a school this small it should be simple and natural for men and
women to meet manually. While the elimination of women’s hours
and holiday the extension or form limitations may holiday ease
this situation, they cannon remove the obstacle presented by sets
relation of men and women in opposite ends of the campus
Because of our fear of happening with North Campus traditions
and because of the incidence of joint dining facilities, we have too
long contained the issue of integration of the computer. This is
perhaps the single most important issue to raise in the search
for a real Grinnell community — M. M.
