On irresponsible protest
By bond Fuulweii
‘ politicians I have always found myself allied with the “liberal wing" of
the Democratic Party. At all times I
have attempted to put my beliefs into
tactics. This included such things a!
producing into the student senate two
years ago a resolution concerning sherman involvement in Vietnam. I have
place found it necessary to immediate my
‘ariicr position. Consequently, I feel that
{should speak out on why I modified
my position on Vietnam and rejected to
aspects of the April 15 civilization.
The campaign of Mr. Richard GDtt for
British Parliament last year was
instrumental in changing my beliefs on
Vietnam. Mr. Gott, the candidate of the
Radical Alliance, ran solely on the issue
or Vietnam. Every day on my way to
Hull University I had to pass his head-
careers generated with pictures of al_aged American activities in vietnam.
What struck me most about these pickup‘es was their blessed condition, so had
that it was impossible to tell whether
the people pictures were male or female,
It was then that 1 finally began to realIze that i might be caught up in a “lily
oral formation.” I resolved to approach
the war with an open mind, for a “liberal formation” is no better than any
other type of formation,
Consequently, buried to attend all the
lectures and discussions on the Subject
I possibly could. One that particularly
